<TITLE> Azeri opposition reporter stabbed: newspaper owner </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BAKU, March 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Unknown attackers stabbed a reporter from Azerbaijan's leading opposition newspaper in what one of its owners said was an attempt by the authorities to gag the paper before a presidential election this year. Agil Khalilov, a leading reporter for the Azadlyq (Freedom) paper, was stabbed in the back late on Thursday as he returned home from work, the paper's general director Azer Akhmedov told Reuters. Khalilov managed to call for help and underwent surgery. He is now in a serious but stable condition, Akhmedov said. "The authorities are trying to halt Azadlyq before the polls ... We believe it was an attempted murder," he said. "The paper's staff have all received various threats, while financial barriers are being set up for the paper." Officials could not be reached for comment. In the past, officials have rejected allegations that they have been involved in attacks on journalists. Khalilov had written about corruption and land sales in the capital Baku. Azerbaijan, a Caspian Sea state in the southern Caucasus where current President Ilham Aliyev succeeded his father Haydar Aliyev shortly before Haydar's death in 2003, is due to hold a presidential election in October. Ilham Aliyev is expected to be re-elected easily. "Today we will raise the issue of these reprisals with the offices of the Council of Europe, the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe and the United States embassy," Akhmedov said. The West has criticised Azerbaijan for tough treatment of journalists. Azeri officials say they respect media freedom. Last week, a court sentenced Azadlyq's editor-in-chief Ganimat Zahid to four years in jail for hooliganism, charges he called "absurd and fabricated". Azerbaijan is fast becoming an important oil supply route to the West and foreign oil firms have invested billions of dollars to develop its hydrocarbon rich
